{"id":"345","name":"Weekly restrictions","tagline":"A description to schedule a random selection of all day events for the next days","icon":"ios12 c3679049983 g59770","latest":"593","description":"\n\t\t\t\t\t<p><strong>the idea behind</strong>  </p>\n<p>The idea for this shortcut started when I wanted to take a break from a couple of bad habits I have; basically I want to push myself to stay free from a bad habit for at least a day, in order to verify that I am not dependent on ite and to have more time for different things, diversifying my week.  </p>\n<p><strong>what it does</strong>   </p>\n<p>When importing you will choose a list of <em>\"restrictions\"</em>: for example, I want to have a day a week without browsing reddit, or watching youtube videos, or gaming.<br>\nI think the ideal list should be of seven items; in this way you run it at the beginning of each week and have a different week each time.<br>\nYou can be creative obviously; for example, I put in a \"free day\", in which I have no restrictions, and a \"only reading\" day, to motivate myself to read a book.<br>\nAfter you choose your list, when you run the shortcut you will have in the calendar an all day event each day for the next <em>n</em> days <em>(where n is the number of items in the list you set up)</em>.  </p>\n<p><strong>how it works</strong>   </p>\n<p>It's pretty simple; it uses a list, then <em>repeat with each</em>: each time it chooses a random item and adds an event on <em>k</em> days from the current day <em>(where k is the iteration number (e.g. the first random item is put on the next day, the second one is put on the second next day etc)</em></p>\n\t\t\t\t","releasenotes":"<p><strong>1.00 - Oct. 19, 2018, 10:19 a.m.</strong></p>"}